LLOOK
=====

The llook ("llookout") command is a land unit's short-range "eyes on
the ground" check — the land-unit counterpart to 'look'/'lookout'
(ships, see 'info look'). It reveals the 7 hexes immediately around
the unit (itself plus its 6 neighbors, land only), and separately
reports any foreign land units and grounded planes nearby.

COMMAND
-------
  llook UNIT-SPEC     Look out from unit(s) matching UNIT-SPEC
  llookout UNIT-SPEC  Same command, long name
  llook *             Look out from every eligible owned unit
  llook c             Look out from every unit in army c

UNIT-SPEC accepts a uid, a uid range, a comma list, "*", "~" (units
with no army assigned), or a single letter naming an army.

ELIGIBILITY
-----------
  The unit needs at least 1 militia aboard to look out, UNLESS it's a
  spy-flagged unit (spies don't need militia). It must not be stowed
  on a ship or another land unit.

WHAT IT SHOWS
-------------
  1. The 7-hex patch around the unit (self + 6 neighbors), for any
     non-water tile — same as 'look', see 'info look' for the exact
     ownership/rounding rules. Updates your bmap for those tiles.

  2. Any foreign land unit within visual range: "Nation #N <type>
     (approx N mil) @ x,y" — militia count is always shown rounded
     to the nearest 20, never exact, even for your own recon. Spy
     units are only sometimes detected (worse odds the more efficient
     the spy is).

  3. Any foreign plane within visual range, as long as it's grounded
     (not stowed on a ship/unit, not currently on a mission):
     "Nation #N <planetype> @ x,y".

  Range depends on your unit's own spy stat (a per-type constant,
  tech-scaled) and current efficiency. Target land units additionally
  use their own type's visibility stat; planes use a fixed value.

EXAMPLES
--------
  llook *          Look out from every eligible owned unit.
  llook 5          Look out from unit 5 only.
  llook c          Look out from every unit in army c.

SEE ALSO
--------
  info look        The ship counterpart
  info lradar      Longer-range terrain sweep, no enemy-unit detail
  info army        Group land units so a letter selects the whole group
